SIMPLE: rhetorician
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rhetorician
<hw>Rhet`o*ri"cian</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>rh⟦eacute⟧toricien</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>One well versed
in the rules and principles of rhetoric.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The understanding is that by which a man becomes a mere logician
and a mere <qex>rhetorician</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>F. W.
Robertson.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A teacher of rhetoric.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The ancient sophists and <qex>rhetoricians</qex>, which ever had
young auditors, lived till they were an hundred years old.</q>
<rj><qau>Bacon.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>An orator; specifically, an artificial orator
without genuine eloquence; a declaimer.</def>
<rj><au>Macaulay.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rhetorician</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rhetorician
<hw>Rhet`o*ri"cian</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Suitable to a master of
rhetoric.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧With <xex>rhetorician</xex> pride.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Blackmore.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rhetorize</ent>⟦br⟧
